Reviewed `src/blog/people/drafts/Sadie-Sink.md` and appended a `FRESH EYES REVIEW` block at the bottom (no body edits).

The two biggest issues I flagged:

1. **Taylor Swift / "All Too Well" is nearly invisible** — arguably her second-most-famous role, and Swift isn't even named in the body (it appears only as "the All Too Well girl" plus one table row). Swift hand-picked her, she leaned on "years of research as a Swiftie" to play it, and the Dylan O'Brien age-gap drove its own discourse. A reader who knows Sink expects this, and there's an unused Type-6 read right there: a devoted Swiftie entrusted by an authority she revered with the fandom's most loaded song — and she answered with homework.

2. **The doubt thesis is restated one too many times** — the diagnosis section and the whole "Why Sadie Sink Runs on Self-Doubt" section overlap heavily on the same Harper's Bazaar quotes, so it starts to drum rather than deepen. Same with the "protection/memeable" note across the epigraph, Texas, and protection sections.

Strongest thing to preserve: the "You are fourteen…" inner-thought paragraph — the one genuine felt-interior moment in the piece.

Sources:
- [All Too Well: The Short Film (Wikipedia)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All_Too_Well:_The_Short_Film)
- [Sadie Sink relied on 'years of research as a Swiftie' (Billboard)](https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/sadie-sink-years-research-swiftie-acting-taylor-swift-all-too-well-video-1235749335/)
